[Student "S"]
{<b><i></i></b>The question is: Do you use Transfers after a 1NT OVERCALL? And in particular, can you bid the opponent's suit and have it mean a transfer instead of a cue-bid? This is something you and your partner need to agree on - as for me and my partner, we think 2\D is a transfer. Partner replies 2\H.  

<b><i></i></b>The question is: Do you use Transfers after a 1NT OVERCALL? And in particular, can you bid the opponent's suit and have it mean a transfer instead of a cue-bid? This is something you and your partner need to agree on - as for me and my partner, we think 2\D is a transfer. Partner replies 2\H. 

With 10 points you are between Invitational and Game-forcing. Which means you bid either 2NT or 3NT, whichever suits your fancy. Today let's say it is 3NT which partner converts to 4\H.

The contract would be 4\H played by South.

North plays 4\H. East leads the \D9. West wins the first trick with the \DA, then plays \DQ. You take your \DK now, fearing that the next one could be ruffed by East.

Loser List: \S = 1 : \H = 1 : \D = 2 : \C = 1 :: Total = 5

You hope West, who opened the bidding, (as East before the hands were rotated), will have the \SK, which would reduce your losers to 4.

You win the second \D and play your \HQ, taken by West with the \HK. He cashes the \DJ, East following, then exits with a small \H. 

Win this trump and play one more, pulling West's last trump and ending in dummy. Play a \S to your \SQ (which wins) then play \SA and ruff a \S in dummy. West follows with the \S7, \SJ and \SK. Now you must try the \C finesse, but through whom? 

Is it a 50-50 guess? Or is West more likely to have the \CQ since he had the opening hand? 

No, it is not a 50-50 guess. No, West doesn't have the \CQ, East does. If you watched the cards that West has played you will realize he started with 3-3-4-3 distribution. You will also know that he started with 14 points outside the \C suit. If he had the \CQ he would have a balanced 16 point hand and would have opened 1NT, not 1\D. So East has the \CQ.

You can go through 100 hands and on 99 of them it won't matter if you pay attention to the cards played by the defenders or not.

But if you don't pay attention on all 100 of them you will miss the one time where your attention was needed.}
[Play "W"]D9

