[Student "S"]
{In the old days (before transfer bids) you could have just bid a "drop-dead" 2\D. But those days are gone so you must improvise. You bid 2\S, transferring partner to \Cs.

Partner says 3\C;  

In the old days (before transfer bids) you could have just bid a "drop-dead" 2\D. But those days are gone so you must improvise. You bid 2\S, transferring partner to \Cs.

Partner says 3\C; 

You now bid 3\D and partner knows to pass.

East plays 3\D. South leads the \SQ. North overtakes and plays \S A K 9.

Loser List: \S = 2 : \H = 1 : \D = ? : \C = 0 :: Total = 3 + ?

Rather than trying to figure out how many losers this \D holding may produce, approach it from the other direction; you can only afford ONE loser, so you assume the cards lie in a way that will give you that result. 

That means that the \Ds must be splitting 3-2, and it also means that you must knock out the \DA without using either the \DK or \DQ. Can you do it? 

Your only hope is for South to hold a doubleton \D A x. You ruff the third \S, then play a small \D toward dummy's \DQ. When this wins the trick, play another \D, and duck in your hand. If South's \DA falls you will be golden. 

There are times when your only hope of making a contract is if the defender's cards lie in a particular way.

When this happens you should play as if they actually <b>DO</b> lie in that way, even though it may be against the percentages.

This hand is a perfect example - your only hope was for South to hold \D A x, so -  you base your plan on South holding \D A x.}
[Play "W"]SQ

